node.text:
Growth comes from drive, consistency, and dedication. Possessing a lack of these qualities will prevent us from reaching our goals. The key is creating a routine around what you want to do and continue doing it until it becomes a habit. It takes the average person 66 days to form a habit, but it's smooth sailing to reach your destination once you establish that.

When I tell people my daily routine, they're generally shocked, not by how long or hard it is, but how consistent I am with it. While aspects of it change daily, the fundamental practice is there. Every day I begin with 30 minutes of meditation, followed by 45 to an hour-long breath practice and about a two-hour yoga/handstand practice. I do this all before I have my coffee. This video is a little cut of my daily movement. For me, it's harder to skip my practice, but this comes down to why I do it. I feel better physically, mentally, and emotionally when I practice than when I don't. I can give you a hundred more reasons, but I think it's more important you affirm your motivation to find what moves you.

node.text:
5 Days, 20 students, 35 hours of meditation and pranayama, ridiculously challenging vinyasa and hours and hours upside down! I’m so proud of this group for their dedication, perseverance and unbelievable growth over the past week. Some students came not being able to do a handstand for more than a few seconds and left being able to hold a free standing handstand for 2 minutes straight! I would have never thought was possible. Everyone progressed so much in their practice. You yogis are amazing!

Huge thanks to @studentsoftheun1verse for coming everyday to film and create this beautiful videos for me to share with you. All 5 days are up in my IGTV! Check them out!

I can’t wait to do this again next year!

Epic day of handstands! Today was lots of flag work and long holds, plus one arm handstand training. The practice has been hard, sweaty and super intense but everyone is still giving so much! It’s been really inspiring to see their level of strength and determination and willingness to try all kinds of craziness!

Video by @studentsoftheun1verse

node.text:
Balance is a condition of action not a state of being.

Life seeks equilibrium through cyclical or oscillating cycles. Yoga philosophy identifies this balancing flow of energy by describing it through three “Gunas.” The first Guna, “Rajas,” represents expanding energy, and our state of doing. “Tamas” symbolizes energy that contracts and descends, and gives us the sentiment of having. “Sattva,” is the Guna of balance and harmony, as in the state of being. Sattva is the energy of ascension and growth, our spiritual growth. 

The three Gunas cycle into each other to create harmony just as winter becomes spring, then summer, to autumn. When we get attached to being or feeling a certain way, we resist the flow of balance and become like a stone in a river, creating turbulence all around us. Rajas expands until exhaustion, tamas contracts into stagnation, magnifying our attachments, and sattva can only arise when the other two gunas are in harmony. 

When we search for balance in our lives we need to learn how to transition from one state to another. Experience the highs and lows without attachment or aversion.

If, at first, you don't succeed, try and try again. Or quit and do something different!

There are many different approaches to training, skills, flexibility, strength, or life in general. Some approaches work well for one thing and not at all for another.  While repetition may be the key factor for learning most skills, sometimes, when we meet repeated failure, it's good to try something different and come back to it in the future, or maybe not at all.

In life, it gets more complicated. When we put all our effort into something that doesn't yield growth, that effort goes to waste and consumes time that could be used for something more beneficial. For example, working a job that isn't fulfilling or staying in an unhappy relationship won't improve if you continue working the same things that brought you to your current state. If doing the same yields the same, or doing something different doesn't improve anything, then quitting might be the best option. 

Quitting can be harder than staying with it. The saying, "better the devil you know than the one you don't," perpetuates this idea of fearing the unknown. "If I quit this, what will I do?  What will happen to me?" But the unknown doesn't need to be scary; it's just unknown. Quitting creates space for new opportunities and growth. I used to think that quitting meant I was a failure, but sometimes it's the most courageous and intelligent thing to do.

node.text:
People don't care about what you know; they only want to know that you care. 

When I became a yoga teacher, I was worried that I didn't know enough. I thought I needed to have a super deep understanding of the poses, sequencing, anatomy, and yoga philosophy to offer anything of value. But knowing these things doesn't mean anything if you don't care about your students. I've taken plenty of classes from knowledgeable teachers that couldn't care less about me. And, I've had teachers with little yoga knowledge but cared enough to know my name or be a shoulder to lean on when I need it.

As I stuff my 200-hour students going through this training with me with theory, anatomy, and philosophy, I hope this is the lesson they leave with.

We don't change lives with knowledge but with compassion.

node.text:
I've wanted to write this post for a while now, but I've been reluctant. Maybe cause I know it's not a big deal to most people, and it's kind of a big deal to me, so it feels disconnected. But it is something that I want to share, and you don't have to care about everything I share!

Since June of 2015, I've been in an exclusivity contract with Alo yoga, and I haven't worn anything else since then. I feel blessed for that opportunity and the extra income they provided, especially when I signed with them when I was making much less as a yoga teacher. But I have to say that I am beyond happy that my contract with them is over and I have the freedom to wear whatever I want! It sounds silly, but imagine only wearing one brand for over six years. Also, my obligation to tag the brand in every post often took away from the message I wanted to share.

I'm also really excited to say that I have left Alo Moves, and I will no longer be creating content with them! This change will allow me to create content independently and share everything that I want without restrictions! But it'll be a little while until I get my platform up, especially since I have two back-to-back teacher trainings coming up. I have so much I want to share with you, and I am beyond excited!

Wearing whatever the f*ck I want!

You're only going to find what you search for. My physical practice is multifaceted. My inspiration for movement goes far beyond being fit, feeling healthy, or doing fun handstands and arm balance transitions. I love the physical benefits, but mental and emotional aspects have been far more valuable than any one-arm balance could offer me.

I've put thousands of hours into my handstands. Every one of those hours I've dedicated has taught me patience, self-discipline, drive, determination, perseverance, what it feels like to fall a thousand times and only to fall again. Knowing that I'll never fail at anything if I never give up. I've learned to trust myself, forgive myself, love myself, and that I have nothing to prove to myself, much less anyone else.

But here's the catch. I was only able to gain that from my practice because that is why I practice. It's not to have a perfect handstand; the handstand is the side effect. Become a better human is the direct result. The means don't matter if your motivation is misunderstood.

node.text:
Stories are how we learn, how we relate, how we communicate. Most people would rather listen to a story than hear a fact sheet. The positive stories we hear can captivate, inspire, and motivate us to be better versions of ourselves. Stories of pain and suffering can evoke in us compassion and empathy for others. Stories are deeply ingrained into our culture, our relationships, how we see ourselves and how we relate to the world around us. The stories charged with emotions, based on experiences that are closest to our own, have the power to touch us the most. 

However, the more personal the story gets, the further we move away from the truth. This isn't necessarily bad unless it is a story we are telling ourselves that's creating pain and suffering. Bad moments are a part of life. We experience them often, but it's the stories we create around these moments that lead to bad days, bad weeks, bad years, or longer. Stories are designed to perpetuate the past, and we get locked in that story, creating an endless loop of suffering. The more powerful the story, the harder it is to escape. The only way to break free from the suffering is to free yourself from the story. But liberation from our stories can be harder than reliving the story itself. Or is it? Is this idea just another story we tell ourselves? Letting go of the past is so difficult because we created a story that we believe to be true, that says, letting go of the past is hard. Let the next story you create tell yourself that it's only a story, and you have all the power to let it go. Because we can't create new stories when we are holding on to the old ones.

node.text:
Non-attachment is a popular concept in yoga and eastern philosophy, but it's also one that is met with a lot of resistance. -Why would we not want to be attached to the people we love?... Right?

I believe much of our difficulty with non-attachment is not with the philosophy but our definition of the word on which this philosophy is based. Connection and attachment are not true synonyms; likewise, non-attachment does not equate to non-connection.

Everything is connected, displaying as different aspects of the whole. (The "whole," meaning the totality of existence and our recognition of being a part of that whole, not apart from the whole.) Connection is fluid; it allows for change but always remains connected. Attachment, however, is our desire for things to stay the same. -I like how this person makes me feel, so I don't want to lose that. And I think by holding on to them, I can keep this feeling in my life.

But as we know, change is a fundamental truth of the universe. To be attached to something or someone remaining unchanged is a fantasy. When change inevitably happens, we experience suffering from that separation. The more attached I am, the greater my suffering will be from what I perceive as loss because my core belief is that we are different. When we believe that we are one, there is nothing to lose. I'm not only talking about death, but also a loss of a relationship or people just changing and growing to be someone different than who we wanted them to be. We are constantly changing. We also can suffer when we become attached to who we used to be.

To be attached and to suffer is human. It's not wrong, but it is a choice we make to live in the fantasy that we are different or that things can remain unchanged. When we lose someone close, we immediately feel pain from their separation, created from the attachment, but over time, the pain fades, and what remains is our love for them through which we are connected.

This handstand to one arm peacock transition was one of the first advanced transitions I learned about ten years ago. My technique has changed over the years, as it has in almost everything I practice. But what hasn't changed much has been my approach. While this transition may look much more calisthenics than yoga, it's yoga that has allowed me to do this ten years later.

Sthira and sukha roughly translate as effort and ease. I could write pages on breaking down these concepts, but I'll keep it short for now. I practice for longevity. Age is a number; however, getting old comes from your body breaking down, usually from lack of movement but also from pushing too hard, which leads to injuries. While I've had injuries throughout the years, they have come from other sports outside of yoga, and it's been yoga that has healed me. From the beginning, my yoga practice has been based on a balance of ease and effort. No matter how hard I train, I maintain a softness, especially in my mind. Balance and alignment are not just concepts for yoga poses but essential for life.

"Superman didn't become Superman. Superman was born Superman. When Superman wakes up in the morning, he's Superman. His alter ego is Clark Kent. His outfit with the big red "S" that's the blanket he was wrapped in as a baby when the Kents found him. Those are his clothes. What Kent wears - the glasses, the business suit - that's the costume." -Quentin Tarantino

I think many of us are searching for greatness, not realizing the inherent greatness that's already within us. We hide our true nature to blend in with the mediocrity we're surrounded by until we feel like that's who we really are. Then we look to the few who truly stand out and wonder why they are different. 

We excuse our lack of eminence, juxtaposed against other's greatness, by saying they must have been born with special talents, or intellect, or strength that I don't possess. And so the costume we don to blend in becomes our identity. Because standing out with greatness means you have to stand out, set yourself apart from the masses, and let your true identity be known to the world. Don't go around thinking your Clark Kent, when in actuality, you're Superman.

node.text:
I was asked the other day, "what's the opposite of fear?"

I commonly hear yogis state that "love" is the opposite of "fear." This may be your truth based on your definitions of fear and love. Everyone's answer comes from a personal relationship of our individual experience. We will all experience these contrasts differently. This is not a case for arguing viewpoints, but one for understanding each other's views to help expand our own. Fear has never been very prevalent in my life; my fears are generally mild and rarely felt. My fears stem more from an attachment to love rather than an opposition to love. I fear losing people I care about, not being able to help others in their time of need, and treating people in a way they perceive as hurtful. All fears are irrational by nature, including my fears, and this post isn't about defining fear but finding its antithesis. To which I responded, "I believe acceptance is the opposite of fear." She told me that "acceptance" wasn't an acceptable answer because "acceptance" isn't an emotion but an idea or a thought. 

Are thoughts and emotions really two separate things? They're obviously different, but I believe they are two expressions on a sliding spectrum that reveal the mind's projected reality. Thoughts represent our logic, ideas, stories, and mental chatter. Emotions declare our mood, circumstances, and relationships. These two are co-dependent in the complete representation of the heart/mind. They're not interchangeable and we also cannot separate one from the other. We can express thoughts about our feelings and have deep emotions about what we think. The two are always connected in how we experience them, and both draw from the heart and the mind. When we learn not to separate our feelings from our thoughts and vice versa, we can combine the power of both to create a broader expansion of awareness to the origins and interpretations of our minds. By removing the semantic separation, which only truly exists in the form of our limited language, we can give our minds the freedom of wholistic expression and a deep understanding of the self and our connection to the world.
